ABOUT THE CODE:
This code fits a Gaussian line profile to 2 chunks of spectra (assuming a doublet) with up to 8 line components in each chunk. Our code uses NumPyro to implement a No U-Turn Sampler (NUTS) in order to fit the following Na I line parameters:
- the centre wavelength of each component
- the optical depth of each component
- the line width of each component 
- the surface fill fraction of each component (fraction of the stellar disc being covered by the obscuring cloud)
- the polynomial degree and its coefficients to fit the continuum

GETTING STARTED:
This code is written in Python 3 and requires the following packages (easily installable via apt-get or conda):
- arviz
- astropy
- corner
- jax
- matplotlib
- numpy
- numpyro
- pandas
- scipy
- xarray
- pytables

The code consists of 4 main files:
- run.py: contains the script to run a fit
- parameters.py: contains the priors of the variable sodium lines used in the fitting function
- fitting.py: contains the fitting function
- removed_lines.csv: contains the data points that have been removed from the fits 

One should be able to start the code by simply installing the required packages, downloading the data and the 4 main files, opening a terminal or a command prompt and typing:

python3 run.py

Run.py must be able to properly read your data files and parameter files. Therefore, instructions of where the script reads your data and parameter files are commented along run.py.

All corrections to the data (e.g. telluric subtraction) must be done before this data is fed to run.py. Note that this code assumes the data is in nanometers and vacuum wavelengths and corrected for BERV (barycentric Earth radial velocity) and for the system radial velocity, so these adjustments should also be done before feeding the data to run.py.

Our data was corrected for telluric absorption using Molecfit (Smette et al., 2015, Kausch et al., 2015). The corrected data is stored in HDF5 files in the data folder.

Run.py reads the data files, normalises the data in the region of the doublet lines, and combines the data per night in pairs. Then, run.py reads parameters.py, where the fitting parameters are described, and feed these parameters into fitting.py. Finally, the fits are performed for the doublet lines.

FITS AND RESULTS:
The function fit_lines(), read by run.py and described in fitting.py, currently provides a sped-up version of the fitting algorithm using cpu_cores=2, nwarmup=200, and nsamples=200 with the first (2018-03-29) of the dataset as an example. Data for all 12 nights (32 exposures separated in 18 pairs) are stored in the data folder. 

In order to obtain the fits presented in the manuscript, we used cpu_cores=20, nwarmup=1000, nsamples=1000, which requires more running time. Fit results for all 12 nights of 2018 (32 exposures separated in 18 pairs) using cpu_cores=20, nwarmup=1000, nsamples=1000 are stored in the utils/fits folder.

Please refer to the paper Method Section "Fitting sodium doublet lines" for additional information about the fitting framework.